explanation:
To decide whether any operations in parse_dauth_params constitute dead code (i.e., they are executed but their removal would not affect observable program behaviour) we must know which writes and calls inside the function are externally observable or have side effects. The following symbols are needed and why:

- struct MHD_RqDAuth
  - parse_dauth_params writes many fields into the MHD_RqDAuth object pointed to by pdauth (nonce, opaque, response, username, username_ext, realm, uri, qop_raw, cnonce, nc, userhash, algo3, qop, etc.). To determine whether those writes are observable (and therefore not dead), the layout and names of fields and which fields are exposed/used elsewhere must be known.

- struct MHD_RqDAuthParam
  - The function fills MHD_RqDAuthParam objects (value.str, value.len, quoted). Knowing whether those fields are used by callers or other code determines whether assignments here are remotely observable or removable.

- struct _MHD_cstr_w_len
  - The token matching logic depends on the structure (len, str). Understanding how the token constants are defined and used is necessary to determine whether particular matching branches can occur and therefore whether code in those branches can execute (relevant to reachability of operations that might be dead).

- _MHD_S_STR_W_LEN (macro)
  - This macro produces the static token constants used for name matching. Knowing its expansion ensures token constants are what we expect (literal data) and helps decide whether some token branches are impossible (dead) given build-time constants.

- mhd_assert (macro/function)
  - parse_dauth_params contains many mhd_assert calls. The behaviour of mhd_assert (compile-time/no-op in release, aborting in debug) affects whether those statements are side-effect free or can change program behaviour; that matters for dead-code判断 (removing an assertion that aborts on failure could change behaviour).

- MHD_str_equal_caseless_bin_n_
- MHD_str_equal_caseless_quoted_s_bin_n
- MHD_str_equal_caseless_s_bin_n_
  - These string-comparison utilities are used to compute pdauth->userhash and in token matching. Knowledge of whether they have side effects (they normally do not) and exact semantics (case handling, quoted handling) is needed to know whether the computed boolean result could differ or whether calls are redundant and removable.

- get_rq_dauth_algo
- get_rq_dauth_qop
  - Both are called at the end and their return values are stored into pdauth->algo3 and pdauth->qop. To decide if those calls (and the preceding population of algorithm/qop_raw) are dead, we must know whether these functions are pure (no side effects) and whether their results are observable by callers (see next symbols). If they are non-pure or callers depend on their outputs, the calls are not dead.

- MHD_get_rq_dauth_params_
  - This is the immediate caller (per the static call graph). We must examine how MHD_get_rq_dauth_params_ exposes or uses the parsed pdauth fields and return value; if it forwards pdauth to other code or returns results derived from pdauth, many writes in parse_dauth_params are observable and thus not dead.

- MHD_digest_auth_get_request_info3
- MHD_digest_auth_get_username3
- MHD_digest_auth_get_username
- digest_auth_check_all_inner
  - These functions are listed as callers (through MHD_get_rq_dauth_params_). To determine if writes by parse_dauth_params are observable at program level, we need to know whether these higher-level consumers read the fields set by parse_dauth_params (for example, userhash, algo3, qop, username, response, nonce, etc.). If they do, the corresponding assignments are not dead; if none of these consumers use particular fields, those assignments could be dead. Including these callers lets the next analyst track usage of pdauth fields across call sites and thus judge deadness.

In short, to determine whether any operation inside parse_dauth_params is dead you must know (a) the exact memory model and members written (struct definitions and token macros), (b) the semantics and side-effects of helper functions and macros invoked inside the function, and (c) whether callers consume the values written (callers that receive or inspect pdauth). The symbols above are the minimal set needed to perform that analysis.
